    <h1 class="big-heading">Effects of Drug Abuse</h1>

    <p>

        Substance abuse can harm a person's physical and mental health, as well as their relationships, employment, and
        social life. The following are some specific examples of substance abuse's effects, organized by substance:

    </p>

    <ul class="resources-ul">

        <li>

            <span>Alcohol</span>: Alcohol is a depressant of the central nervous system, and excessive consumption can
            have a variety of negative effects on the body and brain, including liver damage, pancreatitis, an increased
            risk of certain cancers, and mental health issues such as depression and anxiety. Alcohol abuse can also
            contribute to a wide range of accidents and injuries, such as car accidents and falls.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Opioids</span>: Opioids are a type of drug that is commonly used to relieve pain, but they can also be
            extremely addictive. Opioid abuse can have serious consequences for one's physical health, such as
            respiratory depression, overdose, and death. Aside from physical health issues, opioid abuse can lead to
            mental health issues such as depression and anxiety, as well as exacerbate pre-existing mental health
            conditions. It is critical to use opioids only as prescribed by a doctor and to be aware of the risks
            associated with opioid use.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Stimulants</span>: Stimulant drugs can increase happiness and energy, but they can also cause
            depression, fatigue, and an increased risk of dependence, as well as overstimulation of the heart and
            nervous system, injury, mental health issues, and harm to the developing baby during pregnancy. They may
            also cause nasal passage damage and increase the risk of HIV and hepatitis infection if injected. Combining
            stimulants with alcohol or other drugs can increase the risk of adverse effects, especially if you have a
            heart condition.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Cannabis</span>: Cannabis, also known as marijuana, is a psychoactive drug that induces relaxation and
            alters perception. It can, however, raise blood pressure and heart rate, as well as cause lethargy, anxiety,
            paranoia, and psychosis. It may increase the risk of mental health problems such as schizophrenia, impair
            cognitive function, reduce fertility, and increase the risk of lung diseases and heart disease when combined
            with tobacco. It may be especially dangerous for those who have a history of mental illness or a family
            history of mental illness.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Hallucinogens</span>: Hallucinogens are drugs that cause hallucinations and other changes in
            perception by altering an individual's perception of reality. These drugs can increase the intensity of
            sounds and colors, as well as make you feel alert, warm, and chatty. Hallucinogens, on the other hand, can
            cause anxiety, confusion, paranoia, and even psychosis when used for an extended period of time. Memory
            loss, depression, anxiety, overheating, and dehydration have all been linked to them. Hallucinogen abuse can
            also impair judgment and coordination, increasing the likelihood of accidents and injuries.

        </li>


        <li>

            <span>Sedatives</span>: Sedatives are drugs used to relax the body and mind. They are also referred to as
            tranquilizers or CNS depressants. Sedative abuse can cause respiratory depression, overdose, and death. It
            can also cause mental health problems like depression and anxiety, as well as exacerbate pre-existing mental
            health problems. Sedative abuse can also impair a person's ability to fulfill responsibilities and maintain
            healthy relationships.

        </li>

    </ul>

