    <p>

        Substance abuse can have a wide range of negative consequences for a person, their family, and their community.
        These effects can be both social and economic. Some of the consequences of substance abuse include:

    </p>

    <ul class="resources-ul">

        <li>

            <span>Loss of productivity</span>: Substance abuse can impair an individual's ability to work efficiently,
            leading to absenteeism and poor job performance. As a result, the individual may lose their job or miss out
            on promotions, causing financial problems.

        </li>


        <li>

            <span>Strained relationships</span>: Substance abuse can cause conflict and strain in personal relationships
            because the individual may prioritize their substance over their loved ones. This can result in relationship
            problems and a loss of social support.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Increased healthcare costs</span>: Substance abuse can have a negative impact on both physical and
            mental health, resulting in higher healthcare costs for the individual and their family. Medical treatment,
            rehabilitation, and other related services may be included in these costs.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Legal problems</span>: Substance abuse can lead to criminal behavior and involvement with the legal
            system, incurring legal fees and other costs.

        </li>

        <li>

            <span>Impact on children</span>: Substance abuse can have a particularly negative impact on children, who
            may suffer from neglect or abuse as a result of their parent's substance abuse. Children of
            substance-abusing parents may also be more likely to develop substance abuse problems themselves.

        </li>

    </ul>

    <p>

        Substance abuse can be especially harmful to children, who may face neglect or abuse as a result of their
        parents' substance abuse. Children of substance-abusing parents are at a higher risk of developing substance
        abuse problems themselves.

    </p>

