    <p>

        It has been demonstrated that drug abuse has a significant impact on the brain's reward circuit, which is
        responsible for reinforcing positive behaviors. This has the potential to affect the brain's production of
        neurotransmitters such as dopamine, which is involved in the pleasure and reward system. Drug abuse can cause an
        abnormal release of neurotransmitters, which can lead to feelings of pleasure or euphoria.

        <br><br>

        The brain, on the other hand, may eventually adapt to these large surges by reducing the number of receptors
        that can receive signals or producing fewer neurotransmitters. This can make a person feel unable to enjoy
        previously pleasurable activities, or it can cause a person to require more of the drug to achieve the same
        level of reward, a phenomenon known as tolerance. Substance abuse can also cause physical changes in the brain,
        such as tissue shrinkage and decreased blood flow.

        <br><br>

        It can also lead to addiction, in which the brain becomes dependent on the substance to function properly. As a
        result, certain cues in a person's environment or routine can trigger drug cravings, and these cravings can
        persist even in people who have been drug-free for an extended period of time.

    </p>

